Importing and Exploring the Data

diabetes <- read.csv("diabetes2.csv")

Part I

Step 1

Spliting the data set 80-20
set.seed(180710)
train_8020=sample(1:768, 0.8*768)
train_data_8020=diabetes[train_8020, ]
dim(train_data_8020)
[1] 614   9
test_data_8020=diabetes[-train_8020,]
dim(test_data_8020)
[1] 154   9

Step 2

Fitting the multiple logistic regression model
logistic_model_8020 <- glm(Outcome~., data = train_data_8020, family = binomial)
logistic_model_8020

Part III

1. Best Split (70-30)

cat("Accuracy Rate with 80-20 split:", Accuacy_8020, "\n")
Accuracy Rate with 80-20 split: 0.7662338 
cat("Accuracy Rate with 70-30 split:", Accuacy_7030, "\n")
Accuracy Rate with 70-30 split: 0.7792208 
cat("Accuracy Rate with 60-40 split:", Accuacy_6040, "\n")
Accuracy Rate with 60-40 split: 0.775974 
cat("Accuracy Rate with 50-50 split:", Accuacy_5050, "\n")
Accuracy Rate with 50-50 split: 0.7760417 
max(Accuacy_8020,Accuacy_7030,Accuacy_6040,Accuacy_5050)
[1] 0.7792208

The 70-30 split works best for this data set. That is 70% data in train set and 30% in test set.

This is because the 70-30 split has the highest accuracy rate (0.7792208)

2. ROC Curves

library(ROCR)
pred_8020=prediction(result_8020,true.response_8020)
perf_8020=performance(pred_8020,"tpr","fpr")
plot(perf_8020,col="blue",main="ROC curve with 80-20 split")
auc=performance(pred_8020,"auc")
auc@y.values
[[1]]
[1] 0.8266393
abline(0,1,col="red",lwd=1)
legend(0.6,0.3,"AUC_80 = 0.827")
